{
    "name": "Giant Wasp",
    "type": "monster",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Description",
            "type": "section",
            "html": "Giant wasps nearly always form nests, though not like their much smaller cousins. Each nest functions with one leader (the queen), a few workers, and several soldiers. The workers and the queen produce offspring while the soldiers protect the nest and hunt for food. Giant wasp nests are typically found in caves, abandoned houses, or any complex large enough to fit a dozen 10-foot-tall insects.<br/><br/>Giant wasps attack when hungry or threatened, stinging their prey to death. They take dead or incapacitated opponents back to their lairs as food for their unhatched young\u2014the experience of lying in a wasp nest, paralyzed while its grubs feed, is one of nature\u2019s cruelest inventions. Even when part of a nest, giant wasps tend toward solitary hunting, and it\u2019s rare to see more than one at a time."
        }
    ],
    "html": "<i>This horse-sized wasp is covered in yellow and black vertical stripes\u2014its stinger is the size of a sword and drips with venom.</i>",
